The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package. It wraps all static `System.IO` calls behind injectable interfaces.

**Steps:**

1. **Install** `System.IO.Abstractions` (and `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers` for tests).
2. **Inject `IFileSystem`** instead of calling static methods directly:
   ```csharp
   // Before (untestable)
   File.WriteAllText(path, content);
   var text = File.ReadAllText(path);
   Directory.Exists(dir);

   // After (testable)
   public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
   {
       public void Save(string path, string content)
           => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

       public string Load(string path)
           => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

       public bool DirExists(string dir)
           => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(dir);
   }
   ```
3. **In tests**, use the built-in `MockFileSystem`:
   ```csharp
   var fs = new MockFileSystem();
   fs.AddFile("/data/input.txt", new MockFileData("hello"));

   var svc = new MyService(fs);
   Assert.Equal("hello", svc.Load("/data/input.txt"));
   ```

**Why this over a hand-rolled interface?** `System.IO.Abstractions` covers the entire `System.IO` surface — `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `FileInfo`, streams, etc. — so you won't keep expanding a custom interface every time you touch a new API.
